post_text:
The Okoboji Foundation Youth in Philanthropy Initiative is an annual program for high school students intended to empower students to make a lasting positive impact in the Lakes Community by teaching the next generation the importance of community giving.

Students meet once a month and receive community service hours as they learn about the work of the Okoboji Foundation and other nonprofits in the Lakes Community.

Applications are due by September 10th and can be found at www.okobojifoundation.org under the Youth Tab.

- Mr. O'Rourke, Principal, Spirit Lake High School

shared_text:
MEGAN & CO.
March 17 at 12:17 AM ·

After much consideration we have decided to close to retail shop for at least the next two weeks. We will be available for curbside pickup and online shipments. This decision comes from the need to keep those in our community safe and healthy.
Public entrance is closed however, we are here for
*phone calls
*herbal concerns
*calls to refill formulas or teas
*anxiety + fear support formulas
* immune boosting formulas
* a happy smile or wave through the window

As always, we are so happy to be apart of your lives.

#doyourpart #curbsidepickup #coronavirus #fastime #herbalcare #virus #americanlife #wearehereforyou #justcall

post_text:
The students of the Spirit Lake elementary school participated in our annual Winter Blast last Friday.
Winter Blast is a one day, "J term" like day, for our younger students.
Our students get to practice 21st-century skills in a fun and engaging way outside of the traditional school schedule.
Staff and teachers did a great job planning and giving the students learning experiences that they will be able to use for a lifetime!
Thank you to the community partners that volunteered their time for this event. We wouldn't have been able to offer Winter Blast without our community support!

post_text:
For the 4th consecutive year, J-term not only brought experiential learning out of the classroom but out of the country for 10 students through the Haiti Mission Trip.
Highlights include taking 4th graders on a field trip, pouring a cement floor for a family's home, immersing ourselves to live with a Haitian family, delivering rice/beans/dried veggies to families, hosting multiple VBS's for students, teaching English at an elementary & visiting an authentic market
These only scratch the surface of the many opportunities experienced while in Haiti. Team Haiti was on a mission to serve others and gained so much in return. We are grateful for the experience & for the support of our school & community.

Congratulations to Shai Markwardt who achieved an outstanding personal record on November 23rd in her 2nd International Kettlebell Competition as a member of the Junior USA Marathon Team. She recorded 430 Reps in 30 minutes!

post_text: Busy day at Spirit Lake Elementary. Mel's Coffee cart traveled to Dickinson County courthouse where they made and sold coffee to all the employees in the court house. Back in the building, Bonfire Marketing & Web Co. connected with students to bring "Starbooks" to life in their 1st grade classroom connection! Way to connect SLES!
